## Description

`playerSystem.js` loads character modules using naming conventions with no validation that the expected exports exist.

### Location
`public/scripts/thePlayer/playerSystem.js` lines 597–599

### Code
```js
const name = config.name; // 'Stella', 'Ben', 'Graham'
this.currentPlayer = characterModule[characterId]; // stella, ben, graham
this.updateFunction = characterModule[`update${name}`];
this.drawFunction = characterModule[`draw${name}`];

if (!this.currentPlayer || !this.updateFunction || !this.drawFunction) {
    throw new Error(`Character module '${characterId}' is missing expected exports`);
}
```

### Problem
- Character loading relies on a naming convention: entity = `characterId`, update = `update${Name}`, draw = `draw${Name}`
- The validation check throws a generic error, but:
  - A typo in the character config (e.g., `name: 'stella'` lowercase) silently produces wrong export names (`updatestella` instead of `updateStella`)
  - Adding a new character requires knowing this undocumented convention
  - No type checking or IDE autocomplete support for dynamic property access
- The error message helps debugging, but the fragile pattern invites bugs

### Suggested Fix
Use a standardized export pattern:
```js
// In character module:
export default {
    entity: stella,
    update: updateStella,
    draw: drawStella
};

// In playerSystem:
this.currentPlayer = characterModule.entity;
this.updateFunction = characterModule.update;
this.drawFunction = characterModule.draw;
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** MEDIUM — fragile pattern that breaks silently on naming mismatches

## Description

The control module registers a `DOMContentLoaded` listener without checking `document.readyState` first. If the module loads after DOMContentLoaded has already fired, the listener never runs.

### Location
`public/scripts/thePlayer/control.js` lines 1015–1028

### Code
```js
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    bootstrapKeybindsFromConfigUI();
    setupInventoryControls();
    setupUIShortcuts();

    if (!isMobile()) {
        ['mobile-interact-btn','joystick-area'].forEach(id => {
            const el = document.getElementById(id);
            if (el) el.style.display = 'none';
        });
    }
}, { signal: controlsAbortController.signal });
```

### Problem
- `DOMContentLoaded` fires only once, when the initial HTML document has been completely loaded and parsed
- If `control.js` is loaded as a deferred module or dynamically imported after the DOM is ready, this event has already fired
- The callback never executes → `bootstrapKeybindsFromConfigUI()`, `setupInventoryControls()`, and `setupUIShortcuts()` are never called
- Controls may not be fully initialized

### Suggested Fix
Check `document.readyState` before registering the listener:
```js
function initControls() {
    bootstrapKeybindsFromConfigUI();
    setupInventoryControls();
    setupUIShortcuts();
    // ... mobile check
}

if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initControls, { signal: controlsAbortController.signal });
} else {
    initControls();
}
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** MEDIUM — controls may not initialize if module loading order changes

## Description

In `animalAI.js`, the bull sound cooldown resets before confirming the sound actually played. If AudioManager isn't ready or fails, the cooldown still resets but no sound was heard.

### Location
`public/scripts/animal/animalAI.js` lines 204–217

### Code
```js
if (this.assetName === 'Bull') {
    const now = performance.now();
    if (now - this._lastSfxTime >= this._sfxCooldownMs && Math.random() < 0.25) {
        const audio = getSystem('audio');
        if (audio && audio.playSfx3D) {
            audio.playSfx3D('bull_bellow', this.x, this.y, { category: 'animal' });
            this._lastSfxTime = now;
            this._sfxCooldownMs = 20000 + Math.random() * 20000;
        }
    }
}
```

### Problem
- `playSfx3D` is called, then cooldown is immediately reset
- If `playSfx3D` fails internally (AudioContext suspended, buffer not loaded, user gesture required), the cooldown is still consumed
- The bull appears silent for 20–40 seconds even though no sound played
- On the next check after cooldown, it may fail again — creating a cycle of silent cooldown resets

### Suggested Fix
Check the return value of `playSfx3D` before resetting cooldown:
```js
const played = audio.playSfx3D('bull_bellow', this.x, this.y, { category: 'animal' });
if (played) {
    this._lastSfxTime = now;
    this._sfxCooldownMs = 20000 + Math.random() * 20000;
}
```
This requires `playSfx3D` to return a truthy value on success (or a Promise).

### Impact
- **Severity:** MEDIUM — bull sounds may be silently suppressed for extended periods

## Description

The `WeatherSystem` doesn't listen for `languageChanged` events. Season names displayed in the UI stay in the old language after switching.

### Location
`public/scripts/weather.js` lines 94–114

### Code
```js
function updateWeatherUIPanelContent() {
  const els = _getWuiElements();
  if (!els) return;

  if (els.time) els.time.textContent = WeatherSystem.getTimeString();
  if (els.weekday) els.weekday.textContent = WeatherSystem.getWeekday();
  if (els.day) els.day.textContent = String(WeatherSystem.day);
  if (els.season) els.season.textContent = WeatherSystem.getSeasonName();

  // Update labels for language changes
  if (els.dayLabel) els.dayLabel.textContent = `${t('time.dayLabel')}:`;
  if (els.seasonLabel) els.seasonLabel.textContent = `${t('time.seasonLabel')}:`;
  if (els.weatherLabel) els.weatherLabel.textContent = `${t('time.weatherLabel')}:`;
  // ...
}
```

### Problem
- `updateWeatherUIPanelContent()` is called on each frame/tick to update time
- Labels (`dayLabel`, `seasonLabel`, `weatherLabel`) use `t()` so they update dynamically
- However, `getSeasonName()` and `getWeekday()` may return cached/pre-computed values
- If these methods cache the translated string, it won't update when language changes
- The weather system has no `languageChanged` event listener to force a re-render

### Suggested Fix
Add a `languageChanged` listener in the weather system initialization:
```js
document.addEventListener('languageChanged', () => {
    // Force refresh of any cached translated strings
    updateWeatherUIPanelContent();
});
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** MEDIUM — weather panel shows mixed languages after language switch

## Description

When `pickNewState()` is called in `animalAI.js`, `this.frameIndex` is not reset to 0. This causes frame skipping and visual glitches when animation state changes mid-sequence.

### Location
`public/scripts/animal/animalAI.js` lines 167–180, 190–210

### Code
```js
update() {
    const now = performance.now();
    if (now - this.stateTimer > this.stateDuration) {
        this.pickNewState();  // ← frameIndex not reset here
        this.stateTimer = now;
    }
    if (this.state === AnimalState.MOVE) {
        this.move();
    }
    this.updateAnimation(now);
}

pickNewState() {
    if (Math.random() > 0.6) {
        this.state = AnimalState.MOVE;
        // ... sets target position, duration
    } else {
        this.state = AnimalState.IDLE;
        // ... sets duration
    }
    // ← frameIndex never reset to 0
}
```

### Problem
- When switching from MOVE → IDLE (or vice versa), the frame index from the previous animation state carries over
- If the previous animation had 8 frames and was at frame 6, and the new state's animation only has 4 frames, the index is out of bounds
- Results in visual glitches: wrong frame displayed, animation skipping, or blank frames

### Suggested Fix
Reset frame index at the start of `pickNewState()`:
```js
pickNewState() {
    this.frameIndex = 0;
    // ... rest of state selection
}
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** MEDIUM — visual animation glitches on animals

## Description

`saveSystem.js` reads localStorage once into `_cachedRoot` with no TTL or `storage` event listener. If another browser tab modifies the save data, this tab continues using stale cached data.

### Location
`public/scripts/saveSystem.js` lines 86–112

### Code
```js
_readRoot() {
    // Retornar cache se disponível
    if (this._cachedRoot !== null) {
        return this._cachedRoot;
    }

    try {
        const raw = localStorage.getItem(ROOT_KEY);
        if (!raw) {
            this._cachedRoot = { version: SAVE_VERSION, slots: Array(MAX_SLOTS).fill(null) };
            return this._cachedRoot;
        }
        const parsed = JSON.parse(raw);
        // ... validation ...
        this._cachedRoot = parsed;
        return this._cachedRoot;
    } catch (error) {
        logger.error('Error reading saves:', error);
        this._cachedRoot = { version: SAVE_VERSION, slots: Array(MAX_SLOTS).fill(null) };
        return this._cachedRoot;
    }
}
```

### Problem
1. `_cachedRoot` is set on first read and never invalidated
2. No `window.addEventListener('storage', ...)` to detect cross-tab changes
3. If a player has two tabs open:
   - Tab A saves progress → writes to localStorage
   - Tab B still uses old `_cachedRoot` → reads stale data
   - Tab B saves → overwrites Tab A's progress with stale data
4. Result: **data loss**

### Suggested Fix
Listen for the `storage` event to invalidate cache:
```js
init() {
    window.addEventListener('storage', (e) => {
        if (e.key === ROOT_KEY) {
            this._cachedRoot = null; // Invalidate cache
            logger.info('[SaveSystem] Cache invalidated due to cross-tab change');
        }
    });
}
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** HIGH — potential save data loss/corruption in multi-tab scenarios

## Description

In `buildSystem.js`, the `updateMousePositionThrottled` method schedules a `setTimeout` that continues running after build mode is deactivated. Re-entering build mode can cause both the old and new timeouts to fire.

### Location
`public/scripts/buildSystem.js` lines 152–190

### Code
```js
updateMousePositionThrottled(wx, wy) {
    const now = performance.now();

    if (now - this.lastMouseUpdate >= this.mouseUpdateInterval) {
        this.mouseTile.x = Math.floor(wx / this.gridSize);
        this.mouseTile.y = Math.floor(wy / this.gridSize);
        this.lastMouseUpdate = now;
    } else {
        this.pendingMouseX = wx;
        this.pendingMouseY = wy;

        if (!this.mouseUpdatePending) {
            this.mouseUpdatePending = true;
            setTimeout(() => {
                this.processPendingMouseUpdate();
            }, this.mouseUpdateInterval);
        }
    }
},
```

### Problem
1. `setTimeout` is called but the timeout ID is never stored
2. When build mode is exited, the pending timeout is not cleared
3. `processPendingMouseUpdate()` fires after build mode exit, updating state on a deactivated system
4. Re-entering build mode while old timeout is pending → both old and new timeouts fire
5. `mouseUpdatePending` flag is never reset if build mode exits mid-timeout

### Suggested Fix
Store the timeout ID and clear it on mode exit:
```js
if (!this.mouseUpdatePending) {
    this.mouseUpdatePending = true;
    this._mouseTimeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
        this.processPendingMouseUpdate();
    }, this.mouseUpdateInterval);
}

// In deactivate/destroy:
if (this._mouseTimeoutId) {
    clearTimeout(this._mouseTimeoutId);
    this._mouseTimeoutId = null;
    this.mouseUpdatePending = false;
}
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** HIGH — ghost mouse updates, potential state corruption when toggling build mode rapidly

## Description

`animal/UiPanel.js` adds 3 event listeners in the constructor that are never removed. No `destroy()` method, no `removeEventListener`, no `AbortController`.

### Location
`public/scripts/animal/UiPanel.js` lines 80–86

### Code
```js
document.addEventListener("pointerdown", this._onDocPointerDown, true);
window.addEventListener("resize", this._onResize);
document.addEventListener('languageChanged', () => {
    this.rebuildInterface();
});
```

### Problem
- `pointerdown` listener on `document` — never removed
- `resize` listener on `window` — never removed
- `languageChanged` listener uses an **arrow function**, making it impossible to remove with `removeEventListener` (no reference to the original function)
- When panels are created/destroyed during gameplay, listeners accumulate
- Each leaked listener holds a reference to the UiPanel instance, preventing garbage collection

### Suggested Fix
Use an `AbortController` for all three listeners:
```js
constructor() {
    this._abortController = new AbortController();
    const signal = this._abortController.signal;

    document.addEventListener("pointerdown", this._onDocPointerDown, { capture: true, signal });
    window.addEventListener("resize", this._onResize, { signal });
    document.addEventListener('languageChanged', () => this.rebuildInterface(), { signal });
}

destroy() {
    this._abortController.abort();
    // ... additional cleanup
}
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** HIGH — memory leak when animal UI panels are created/destroyed

## Description

The `audioManager` module has no `destroy()` or `cleanup()` method and is not listed in `gameCleanup.js`. This means audio resources persist after game exit.

### Location
`public/scripts/audioManager.js` (entire file)

### Problem
- No `destroy()` or `cleanup()` method exists
- Not registered in `gameCleanup.js` cleanup sequence
- `AudioContext` is never closed on game exit
- Playing audio and any running intervals persist after cleanup
- Internal cleanup exists for individual tracks (`_endMonitorCleanup`, `_stopCurrentTrack`) but no system-level teardown

### Current state of `gameCleanup.js`
The following systems are cleaned up: PlayerSystem, InventorySystem, ItemSystem, InventoryUI, WorldUI, MerchantSystem, Controls, HouseSystem, ChestSystem, WellSystem, WeatherSystem.

**Missing:** AudioManager, CraftingSystem, AnimalsUI/UiPanel, BuildSystem

### Suggested Fix
1. Add a `destroy()` method to audioManager:
```js
destroy() {
    this._stopCurrentTrack();
    this._stopFog();
    if (this.audioContext && this.audioContext.state !== 'closed') {
        this.audioContext.close();
    }
    // Clear any intervals/timeouts
    // Remove event listeners
}
```
2. Register in `gameCleanup.js`:
```js
const audioManager = getSystem('audio');
if (audioManager && typeof audioManager.destroy === 'function') {
    audioManager.destroy();
}
```

### Impact
- **Severity:** HIGH — memory leak, continued audio playback after game cleanup
- Also see follow-up issue for #11 (event listener leaks)

